viet rule in the Islamic Caucasus. Examining literary representations of social banditry to tell the story of Russian colonialism from the vantage point of its subjects, among numerous other themes, Gould argues that the literatures of anticolonial insurgency constitute a veritable resistance-or "transgressive sanctity"-to colonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCaucasian literaturexHistoryy19th century. 0aCaucasian literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCaucasian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aInsurgency in literature. 0aRussian literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311053800740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300220759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300220759.jpg  a978-3-11-053800-7  YUP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles